Reading bronze.

There are two equivalent ways to read a bronze table — the python dataframe API and plain sequel — and the exam may show you either side of it. Both return a lazy result. Reading a delta table never reads any bytes until an action runs, and the catalyst optimiser pushes column pruning, predicate pushdown, and partition pruning right into the read.

Two variations are worth knowing. You can read a specific delta version using version-as-of, which is how you build a reproducible silver — pinning exactly which bronze snapshot the build ran against.

And you can do a streaming read instead of a batch read, which is what you reach for when silver should update continuously as bronze updates. Same table, just read as a stream.
